ezants]], representing the [[five wounds of Christ]]<ref name=criarmundos>{{cite web |url=https://criarmundos.do.sapo.pt/Portugal/simbolosbandeira.html |title=A Bandeira de Portugal |work=Portugal |publisher=Criar Mundos |date=August 2005 |accessdate=2007-02-19 |language=Portuguese |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061001110542/http://criarmundos.do.sapo.pt/Portugal/simbolosbandeira.html |archivedate=2006-10-01 }}</ref>\n|-\n|{{flagicon|San Marino}}\n|[[San Marino]] ([[Flag of San Marino|flag]])\n|Cross<ref name=\"Pew Research\"/>\n|-\n|{{flagicon|Serbia}}\n|[[Serbia]] ([[Flag of Serbia|flag]])\n|Orthodox Cross<ref name=\"Temperman2014\">{{cite book|last=Temperman|first=Jeroen|title=State-Religion Relationships and Human Rights Law: Towards a Right to Religiously Neutral Governance|year=2010|publisher=Brill Academic |isbn=9789004181489|page=88|quote=The cross on the flag of Dominica represents Christianity while the three colours of which the cross consists stand for the Trinity. The coat of arms depicted on the flag of Slovakia shows a double cross. The flag of the Dominican Republic represents Christianity while the three colours of which the cross consists stand for the Tinity. The coat of arms depicted on the flag of Slovakia shows a double cross. The flag of the Dominican Republic shows the words \"God, Fatherland, Liberty\", an opened bible and a cross (depicted in the coat of arms which is represented in the centre). The 'five-cross-flag' of George shows four small crosses and a large St. George's Cross, referring to the patron saint of Georgia (the national flag of England shows the St. George's Cross as well). The white cross on the flag of Greece symbolizes Greek Orthodoxy. The flag of Moldova shows its coat of arms in the centre: an eagle with a Christian Orthodox cross in its beak. The coat of arms of Serbia, as depicted on the national flag, also shows an Orthodox cross.}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{flagicon|Slovakia}}\n|[[Slovakia]] ([[Flag of Slovakia|flag]])\n|[[Patriarchal cross]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.psp.cz/eknih/1939ssr/tisky/t0015_00.htm |title=O \u0161t\u00e1tnej vlajke, \u0161t\u00e1tnej z\u00e1stave, \u0161t\u00e1tnom znaku a \u0161t\u00e1tnej pe\u010dati |work=Joint Czech\u2013Slovak Digital Parliamentary Library  |publisher=Chamber of Deputies of the Parliament of the Czech Republic |date=June 1939 |accessdate=2013-06-23}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{flagicon|Spain}}\n|[[Spain]] ([[Flag of Spain|flag]])\n|The three crosses represents the [[Trinity]]<ref name=\"Pew Research\"/>\n|-\n|{{flagicon|Sweden}}\n|[[Sweden]] ([[Flag of Sweden|flag]])\n|[[Nordic Cross Flag]]<ref name=\"Jeroen Temperman\" />\n|-\n|{{flagicon|Switzerland}}\n|[[Switzerland]] ([[Flag of Switzerland|flag]])\n|[[Christian cross]]<ref name=\"Foley1996\">{{cite book|last=Foley|first=Carol A.|title=The Australian Flag|date=1 January 1996|publisher=Federation Press|isbn=9781862871885|page=10|quote=The Christian cross, for instance, is one of the oldest and most widely used symbols in the world, and many European countries, such as the United Kingdom, Norway, Sweden, Finland, Denmark, Iceland, Greece and Switzerland, adopted and currently retain the Christian cross on their national flags.}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{flagicon|Tonga}}\n|[[Tonga]] ([[Flag of Tonga|flag]])\n|Christian cross<ref name=EB>{{cite encyclopedia|first=Whitney|last=Smith|encyclopedia=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica|title=Flag of Tonga|url=http://global.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/1355548/flag-of-Tonga|date=24 November 2013|accessdate=9 August 2014|publisher=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica, Inc.}} '''{{subscription required}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{flagicon|Tuvalu}}\n|[[Tuvalu]] ([[Flag of Tuvalu|flag]])\n|Crosses of [[St. George]], [[St. Andrew]] and [[St. Patrick]]\n|-\n|{{flagicon|Ukraine}}\n|[[Ukraine]] ([[Flag of Ukraine|flag]])\n|The yellow represents golden domes ([[cupola]]s) of churches in the country.\n|-\n|{{flagicon|United Kingdom}}\n|[[United Kingdom]] ([[Union Jack|flag]])\n|Crosses of [[St. George]], [[St. Andrew]] and [[St. Patrick]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.royal.gov.uk/MonarchUK/Symbols/UnionJack.aspx |title=Union Jack |publisher=The Royal Household |accessdate=2013-06-23}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{flagicon|Vatican City}}\n|[[Vatican City]] ([[Flag of the Vatican City|flag]])\n|The flag consists of two vertical bands, one of gold ([[flag terminology|hoist]] side) and one of white with the crossed [[Key (lock)|keys]] of [[Saint Peter]] and the [[Papal Tiara]] centered in the white band\n|}\n\n===Islam===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!'''Flag'''\n!'''Country'''\n!'''Religious characteristics'''\n|-\n|{{flagicon|Afghanistan}}\n|[[Afghanistan]] ([[Flag of Afghanistan|flag]])\n|[[Shahadah]] and a [[mosque]], green may represent Islam<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/flags/flagtemplate_af.html |title=Flag Description: Afghanistan |work=World Factbook |publisher=[[Central Intelligence Agency|CIA]] |accessdate=June 21, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110612013757/https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/flags/flagtemplate_af.html |archivedate=June 12, 2011 }}</ref>\n|-\n|{{flagicon|Algeria}}\n|[[Algeria]] ([[Flag of Algeria|flag]])\n|[[Star and crescent]], green color symbolizes Islam<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/flags/flagtemplate_ag.html |title=Flag Description: Algeria |work=World Factbook |publisher=[[Central Intelligence Agency|CIA]] |accessdate=June 21, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130615134039/https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/flags/flagtemplate_ag.html |archivedate=June 15, 2013 }}</ref>\n|-\n|{{flagicon|Azerbaijan}}\n|[[Azerbaijan]] ([[Flag of Azerbaijan|flag]])\n|Green stands for [[Islam]], the [[Hilal (crescent moon)|crescent moon]] is also an Islamic symbol<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-w